Furthermore, the optical detection study followed the Dynamic Light Scattering (DLS) analysis, which revealed that the Ag@CDs treated with Fe3+ had a higher Rh value. When the Rh was computed, it was observed that it had risen to 69.55 nm (Fig. 2 d). It is thus evocative of the fact that negatively charged Ag@CDs cross-link with Fe3+ ions follow-on in aggregation and destabilization, which leads to quenching. Similarly, under the Fe3+ treatment, the zeta potential of the test solutions revealed a change in electrophoretic mobility. The average zeta potential of Ag@CDs with interfering analytes remained negative, except for Fe3+treatment (

                           Table 1

                        ). With an average zeta potential of 7.9 mV, the Fe3+ treatment solution possessed a positive charge. This suggested that treating Ag@CDs with Fe3+ caused the negatively charged surface to be neutralized, resulting in particle instability. The specificity of biogenic CDs synthesized from F. benghalensis L. towards Fe3+ and Ni2+ has previously been described (Ajith et al., 2020). The current study indicates that conjugating biogenic CDs with Ag NPs restricts their selectivity towards Fe3+, i.e., Ag@CDs become more specific. Thus, it provides a chemosensory platform for the specific detection of Fe3+.
